    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The question of who would get what under Gov. George W. Bush's tax-cut plan, while legitimate, is not the real issue (''Bush Tax Plan: The Debate Takes Shape,'' front page, Aug. 26). The question should be what would be done with the money that would become available. If it went to wealthy taxpayers, it would probably be spent on bigger houses or invested in the stock market.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The question of who would get what under Gov. George W. Bush's tax-cut plan, while legitimate, is not the real issue (''Bush Tax Plan: The Debate Takes Shape,'' front page, Aug. 26). The question should be what would be done with the money that would become available. If it went to wealthy taxpayers, it would probably be spent on bigger houses or invested in the stock market.</p>
        <p>But the public sector has major unmet needs. If the surplus went to private taxpayers, who would pay for school repairs and books or build us a new air traffic control system? Which investors would rebuild roads and bridges? There are certain things that only a government can do.</p>
        <p>L. R. JEFFREY  Far Hills, N.J., Aug. 29, 2000</p>
      </block>
